RSY150 cells grown to the mid logarithmic phase and
exposed to oil for 4Â h were imaged by LSCM to view
patterns of nuclear division and tubulin distribution in
the parent cells and the bud. Budding cells with a single
nucleus were considered to be pre-mitosis, representing
those in the G1 or S phase. Cells with nuclei traversing
the parent and budding cells were considered to be in the
anaphase stage of mitosis. Finally, cells having separate
nuclei in both parent and budding cells were considered
to be at a post-mitotic phase, G2/M. For RSY150 control
cells, 52% of the population was in the G1 or S phase;
36% of the cells had undergone mitosis; and the final 10%
were in anaphase (Fig.Â
b, c). On the other hand, RSY150
treated with MIC of CNB oil displayed noticeable dif
ferences in cell cycle distribution, with 39% having not
begun mitosis, 48% having completed mitosis, and 14% in
anaphase, still undergoing nuclear division (Fig.Â
c). Cells
treated with 1/2 MIC were at GI phase (38%), whereas
the dominant number of cells were at G2/M phase, with
no change in the number of cells undergoing anaphase.
Cells treated at MIC with CNB oil showed extended cells
with pseudohyphal formation, however the effect was less
pronounced in cells treated at 1/2 MIC, where large bud
ding cells were observed (Additional fileÂ
: Figure S2a,
b). The data clearly indicate that CNB oil induces tubulin
depolymerisation leading to cell cycle arrest at anaphase.
